 {"id":"flywheel_gateway-4ub","title":"CAAM auth UX follow-ups (device-code, import/upload guidance, BYOA onboarding copy)","description":"## Background

CAAM account onboarding is where users provide and manage BYOA/BYOK authentication material (device codes, OAuth tokens, API keys). This is one of the highest-friction and highest-risk parts of the system:

- Users get stuck on ambiguous auth failures (expired device codes, revoked tokens, missing scopes).
- Users may accidentally persist or paste secrets into unsafe places (logs, screenshots, copied terminal output).
- Without explicit guidance, “it works on my machine” scenarios become support burdens.

This bead focuses on improving the **UX + copy + guardrails** around CAAM onboarding so users can successfully connect accounts quickly, safely, and with clear recovery steps.

## Goals

- Make device-code flows guided and self-explanatory (no need to read docs for the happy path).
- Make persistence and redaction rules explicit (what gets stored, where, and how it is protected).
- Surface common failure modes with actionable fixes, not generic errors.
- Keep everything compatible with the broader CAAM implementation bead (`flywheel_gateway-41h`).

## Scope

### 1) Guided device-code flow UX

- Step-by-step UI with:
  - copy-to-clipboard for codes
  - verification URL link handling
  - countdown timers / expiry visibility
  - polling status with backoff
  - explicit cancel/retry
  - clear mapping of provider failures → recovery actions

### 2) Secure manual auth import/upload copy

- Explicit copy for users who need to import auth material:
  - what formats are accepted
  - what fields are required
  - where data is stored (and that it is encrypted-at-rest)
  - what is never stored
  - how logs and artifacts are redacted

### 3) BYOA onboarding guidance + warnings

- Clear onboarding copy that includes:
  - prerequisites (accounts, scopes)
  - expected rate-limit behaviors
  - common failures and recovery
  - safe defaults and confirmations for risky actions

### 4) "Make risky actions deliberate" UX patterns

- Confirmations + safe defaults
- Prevent accidental persistence
- Ensure sensitive fields are masked and never re-rendered once submitted

## Non-Goals

- Implementing CAAM backend primitives (handled by `flywheel_gateway-41h`).
- Adding provider-specific auth modes beyond the device-code + manual-import UX specified here.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] UX provides a guided device-code flow (clear steps, copy-to-clipboard, polling status, error recovery)
- [ ] Manual import/upload guidance is explicit about what is stored, where it is stored, and how it is redacted in logs
- [ ] Onboarding copy explains prerequisites and common failure modes (revoked tokens, expired device codes, insufficient scopes)
- [ ] UI makes risky actions deliberate (confirmations, safe defaults, no accidental persistence)
- [ ] Doc changes stay aligned with the implemented UI and do not reference any private business details

## Testing Requirements

### Unit Tests
- [ ] Copy helpers and form validation (required fields, scope warnings, expired code states)
- [ ] State machine for device-code flow (idle → pending → authorized/failed)

### E2E Tests
- [ ] Happy path onboarding (mock provider): start device-code → confirm authorized → account becomes healthy
- [ ] Failure modes: expired code, revoked token, missing scope → UI shows actionable recovery steps

### Integration Tests
- [ ] Device-code onboarding API mocks and state transitions (pending → authorized/failed)
- [ ] Token import/upload path persists securely and redacts logs

### Logging
- [ ] Test logs include correlationId + anonymized accountId; secrets are never logged

## References

- `flywheel_gateway-41h`: CAAM Account Management (BYOA + Rotation)
- `flywheel_gateway-y19.21`: PLAN: 16. CAAM Account & Profile Management (BYOA + BYOK)
